firmation of metastases provides critical histological information required for definitive treatment decisions [Data: Entities (19, 20, 137, 136); Relationships (54, 55, 450, 451)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Life Expectancy as a Determinant for Treatment Pathways\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Assessment of life expectancy directs subsequent management in scenarios of recurrence or persistent disease. Entities capturing life expectancy thresholds (>5 years) are linked to further risk stratification, intensive imaging, and consideration for biopsy, establishing a protocol for aggressive versus conservative intervention. Shorter expected survival may prompt symptom control or palliative regimens, whereas longer expectancy supports pursuit of curative intent therapy [Data: Entities (2, 3); Relationships (18, 19, 17, 480)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Progression Pathways Integrate Treatment Response and Disease Resistance\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Entities and relationships outline progression from initial diagnosis, through recurrence and response to primary therapy, towards development of resistance or advanced disease states (e.g., symptomatic progression, M0 CRPC). These transitions are illustrated by links from 'PSA persistence/recurrence' and 'Symptomatic progression' to downstream management options and further staging. The networked entities support a model of dynamic, iterative progression where each new event may prompt a revised clinical strategy [Data: Entities (126, 22, 141); Relationships (377, 60, 480)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Treatment Modalities Include Both Monitoring and Active Interventions\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Entities for treatment options reveal both conservative (monitoring) and active (ADT, abiraterone, radiotherapy) management are considered at several decision points. The choice of treatment is contextual, often driven by the output from staging, recurrence characteristics, and risk profiles. N